### Client-Side Payment Handling with x402 Fetch Wrapper

Source: https://github.com/coinbase/x402/blob/main/examples/typescript/fullstack/miniapp/README.md

Handles payments on the client-side using `@x402/fetch`. It initializes an x402 client, registers the exact EVM scheme with a signer, and then wraps the native `fetch` function. The `fetchWithPayment` function automatically manages the payment process when making requests to protected endpoints.

```typescript
import { x402Client, wrapFetchWithPayment } from "@x402/fetch";
import { registerExactEvmScheme } from "@x402/evm/exact/client";

// Create client and register EVM scheme
const client = new x402Client();
registerExactEvmScheme(client, { signer: wagmiToClientSigner(walletClient) });

// Wrap fetch with payment handling
const fetchWithPayment = wrapFetchWithPayment(fetch, client);

// Make request - payment is handled automatically
const response = await fetchWithPayment("/api/protected");

```

--------------------------------

### Initialize and Use x402 Axios Client (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/coinbase/x402/blob/main/examples/typescript/clients/axios/README.md

This snippet demonstrates initializing the x402 client, registering an EVM payment scheme using a private key, and wrapping an Axios instance with x402 payment capabilities. It then makes a GET request to a local endpoint and logs the response data. Dependencies include @x402/axios, @x402/evm/exact/client, viem/accounts, and axios.

```typescript
import { x402Client, wrapAxiosWithPayment } from "@x402/axios";
import { registerExactEvmScheme } from "@x402/evm/exact/client";
import { privateKeyToAccount } from "viem/accounts";
import axios from "axios";

const client = new x402Client();
registerExactEvmScheme(client, { signer: privateKeyToAccount(process.env.EVM_PRIVATE_KEY) });

const api = wrapAxiosWithPayment(axios.create(), client);

const response = await api.get("http://localhost:4021/weather");
console.log(response.data);
```

