### Initialize and Use x402 Fetch Client

Source: https://github.com/coinbase/x402/blob/main/examples/typescript/clients/fetch/README.md

Demonstrates initializing the x402 client with EVM and SVM signers and wrapping the native fetch function to handle payment-protected requests. This implementation requires valid private keys for both EVM and SVM networks.

```typescript
import { x402Client, wrapFetchWithPayment } from "@x402/fetch";
import { registerExactEvmScheme } from "@x402/evm/exact/client";
import { registerExactSvmScheme } from "@x402/svm/exact/client";
import { privateKeyToAccount } from "viem/accounts";
import { createKeyPairSignerFromBytes } from "@solana/kit";
import { base58 } from "@scure/base";

const client = new x402Client();
registerExactEvmScheme(client, { signer: privateKeyToAccount(process.env.EVM_PRIVATE_KEY) });
registerExactSvmScheme(client, { signer: (await createKeyPairSignerFromBytes(base58.decode(process.env.SVM_PRIVATE_KEY))) });

const fetchWithPayment = wrapFetchWithPayment(fetch, client);

const response = await fetchWithPayment("http://localhost:4021/weather");
console.log(await response.json());
```

